Islam Can be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when the Swiss voters voted for a ban on building minarets and the widespread concern about the alleged Islamisation of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, a thorough and thoughtful report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of the avowedly säkularisiertesten societies of Europe - and be integrated.
Some readers will this new book from admiration for the last work of the author: " Why do the French love " (original title: " Why the French Don't Like Headscarves ") (2006) , an elegant and densely argumentierenden study a contentious issue, which divided the country about one and a half decades and employed and whose effects are still visible.
Bowens neustes book offers a more comprehensive and kühneres spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he would like to know not only what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is happening on the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, which are now the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls " Islamic free " offer.
He is a good listener, he gives debates between teachers and students about the issues that concern them most.
Should a Muslim in a mosque or a City hall (or both
Young Muslims Should be lectured about evolution and rights of homosexuals?
A Muslim woman Can marry a non - Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest - oriented banking system in order to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane matters, he claims, the daily life, in contrast to the political drama, the media.
The author acknowledges a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a well - known name, perhaps with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss - born Arab Muslim scholars and academics.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible, on the one hand and, on the other hand, a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not have all the arguments on their side.
The Conservatives are wary of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists interviewed Bowen, are with their Salafi counterparts - supporters of the puristischen Sunni Islam linked to Saudi Arabia, which is a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires give and take on both sides.
He queries whether French political makers (and the intellectual elite, so passionate the separation of church and state) committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may be a rougher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, which in turn had to make their historic compromise with the secular Republicanism.
He sees a " tightening of the screws " as a growing pragmatism.
Islam can be French? After reading this book, one is tempted to say " yes, but not yet. "
The bleak outlook of the world
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatic than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice is melting at an alarming rate and takes life that can survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests in the newly open water, with diplomats, lawyers, and now also authors in their wake.
Richard Ellis, an author and Illustrator, in " on thin ice " (original title: " on Thin Ice ") , a natural history of the icon of the north, the polar bears.
Bewandert in the complex history and politics of the whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arktiserforscher who have proved themselves in the hunt for the polar bears.
Admiral Nelsons encounter with a polar bears as a brave 14 - year - old Fähnrich sea, only with the rifle his Muskete fought, is certainly a myth, but others are true.
Young bears, which, as they have been caught behind the bodies of their mothers, were recently killed in zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears in a vision.
Even today Zooanlagen typically still have a millionth of the life of wild Alttiers. The climate is rarely appropriate: the Eisbär in Singapore was quite green of the algae that grow in the hollow hair of his skin.
