A change of direction in the ageing China
Wang Weijia and her husband, surrounded by propaganda posters, the lecture that " mother earth is too tired to talk to other children " and " one more baby means one more tomb. "
These lessons have you learned that, as well as government officials in Shanghai, the low birth rate and ageing population in this summer, suddenly began to change course and young couples to have more than one child, their response was immediate and definitive: " under no circumstances ".
We have all of our time and energy invested in a child.
For a second child is nothing more, said Wang, 31, a staff leader with an 8 - month old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one - child policy in China, the two generations of notoriously dicklichen, spoiled Einzelkindern, who affectionately called " little emperors ", has produced a population crisis in the country.
The average birth rate is at 1.8 children per couple, compared to 6 at the time, as this policy came into force, the UN
Department of population issues, while the number of the population 60 years and older in 2020 from 16.7 percent of the population by the year 2050 to 31.1 percent to This is well above the global average of 20 percent.
The imbalance is in rich coastal cities with educated population, such as Shanghai, stronger.
Last year, 60 years and older almost 22 percent of reported residents while the birth rate of one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, the head of the Shanghai population and family planning Commission has said that couples should receive normal reproductive age babies, in order to help the relationship of the ageing population and to alleviate the labour shortage in the future ".
Shanghai will soon " as old -- but not so rich -- such as the industrialised countries, such as Japan and Sweden, " she said.
A gradual easing
Enshrined in the constitution of the country in 1978, China's one - child policy would be the most controversial, which was introduced by the ruling Communist Party until today.
Couples who are against this policy, must reckon with huge fines -- up on her triple annual salary in some regions and with discrimination in the workplace.
Chinese state officials have attributed to this policy, the critical demands on natural resources could be avoided, while human rights activists have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials pregnant women who have already had a child, forced to abzutreiben.
Many couples have had to carry out sex - selective abortions, which an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for population gradually their stance on the one - child policy.
In 2004, they have allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including urban dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife have been Einzelkinder -- and 2007 was the tone of many hard slogans.
Qiao Xiao Chun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing said that government officials recently even more radical changes to allow, for example, two children, couples in which one partner is Einzelkind.
Shanghai was in July, the first Chinese city, which has launched an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters, belehrten family, only to have a child, have been replaced almost overnight of directives, which describe in detail, who for a second child, and how we can apply for the permit.
The city government has sent municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to couples at home and information sheets under the doors.
They also asked, psychological and financial advice for the available, which have more than one child.
The response was not encouraging, said family planning officials.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural town in the outside areas of Shanghai, said that a recovery in the requests from couples to see after the launch of the campaign for a second child, the urban districts reported no change.
In the municipality with a population of 115,000, for example, still only four or five requests per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that the expected number of births in the city despite the campaign still around 165.000 -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai municipal Caolu, said that financial considerations were probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to give her the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juan Juan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and this is legally allowed.
But they have, how many Chinese, only a minor health and life insurance to the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West the one - child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer, whose wife is seven months pregnant with her first child.
Yes, it is robbing us the opportunity to have more than one child.
But The problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples be psychological reasons for their reluctance.
Wang, the personnel chief, said she would like to just one child, because she was also a Einzelkind. " We were the focus of the family and that everyone around us.
We are not accustomed to care for others and do not really want to do this. "
Chen Zijian, a 42 - year - old, a translation company, said it plain.
For parents from the middle class with dual career, through which the birth rate is falling, he said, it is to be successful and we must be selfish.
The age group of 20 to 39 - year - old grew to see their parents during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they want a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, makes huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up their social life for at least two years.
Then there is the question -- " we must rebuild his home " -- and the -- " if the child is 9 months old, have a CV for the best schools. "
Most of his friends are ready, this is a time, said Chen, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to have achieved a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want too many victims.
UN group plan to reduce emissions
The UN - sponsored climate conference which until now by wild postures and has set on Friday with the publication of a document for the next 40 years, recording an ambitious cuts in greenhouse gases, with the industrialized nations in the near future would have to shoulder the biggest burden.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has both the remaining obstacles, as well as the way forward.
But he was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation, the time next week, more than 100 leaders from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, which was created by a special UN working group, is silent on the amount of money from the rich countries to poor countries should be short and long term global warming.
He also offers a range of options for the key questions, including how developed and major emerging countries limit their carbon emissions and how much should be the upper limit of the global rise in temperature, the political decision - makers.
The process will be a great deal of flexibility, John Coequyt, a senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has drafted the six - page document, a 180 - page negotiating text in order to focus on what the leading representatives of the UN climate change, Yvo de Boer described as " the big picture ".
It shows the outline of a possible agreement, in which the industrialized nations together their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared with 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions in the same period 15 to 30 percent.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 2050 by 50 to 95 percent.
The talks on Friday, the European Community has also given a boost by their assurance, over the next three years, 3.6 billion dollars per year to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from the masters of floods and droughts and avoiding deforestation.
The Friday expressed the same verbal fireworks, what the talks in the last week.
The U. S. climate envoy Todd Stern has rejected, the binding cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries, compared with voluntary reductions for major emerging economies, demand, if they are not funded by the industrialized nations.
This train has announced that the Obama administration a tougher line with China, as a representative of the Bush administration, not even two years ago.
The United States will sign an agreement without major emerging countries stand up and take action, so Stern, who also lamented the fact that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave its opinion an hour after the declaration of the Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei, said that the leading US climate negotiator either " common sense " or " highly irresponsible " of him was that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States, China would not help to tackle global warming.
The fact that the future economic direction of the major world powers are at stake, both within the industrial nations, as well as between the industrialized nations and emerging fault lines.
The current fight applies equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to save the planet, with China and the United States because of their respective commitments, while poorer countries argue that the two dozen influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder steps.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers who bear the costs of the Bremsung of greenhouse gas emissions, because even affected countries have begun to act more aggressively, the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions to account for their actions.
It is clear that this is a game, which will develop a new economic domination, Ulate, who is also a regional climate change adviser for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries that are most exposed to the effects of climate change, said that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, though the leading participants say that the talks in the best - case will lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of small island states with 43 members on early Friday morning a 24 - page draft treaty.
Artur Runge - Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states, " political pressure on the whole political process, " in part because they are now united and measures of the emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues must be resolved before the arrival of the government leaders to reach an agreement.
High - level representatives, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese vice Minister entstiegen their aircraft and through the corridors of the meetings behind closed doors and press conferences during the next week.
The sheer scale of the Assembly, 13,000 people daily in Congress Centre and, gitarrespielende activists hold late - night shows, in which they are making fun of the betray and sell, and draft will be passed from hand to hand rather than by e - mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity builds just: almost all the important ministers are now here and will be 60 government leaders in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy of the organization Conservation International.
