United States: Grave record in Zola, estimated at 1.5 million US dollars
A Roman grave record, which the French writer Emile Zola, was on Thursday to 1.5 million US dollars on their value, the art dealer Sotheby's.
This record is two metres long and 63 cm high. It comes from the Third century after Christ and was priced with 150,000 to 250,000 dollars.
The marble, on the " four scenes of Dionysus in a sophistischen architekturdekor, surrounded by Satyren and Bacchusfiguren, is a rare piece. There are only four or five of them, " said Florent Heintz, Vice - President for Roman and Egyptian antiques auction at Sotheby's, on Tuesday told the AFP.
It was sold under hundreds of pieces.
" The sale is ongoing, but this is certainly what the buyer, until now, most of it, " says the spokesman of Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy to the AFP.
The discovery of this acquisition of marble by Emile Zola goes way back.
The record was almost 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the Borghese family at home, then it piece by piece appeared in the French actress Cécile Sorel, die in their Paris hotels to use, and Paul Reynaud, a minister in the Third French Republic and President of the Council, before Marshal Pétain came to power.
The next 50 years are in the dark.
In search of the database of the Louvre Florent Heintz discovered that this record was part of a " heritage of Emile Zola, a year after the death of the author of " Thérèse Raquin " and the Fresko " Rougon - Macquart ", was opened.
